WEBVTT

1
00:00:11.820 --> 00:00:15.820
Hi. I'm here to talk to you about the importance of
嗨。我在这里要和大家谈谈

2
00:00:15.820 --> 00:00:18.820
praise, admiration and thank you,
向别人表达赞美，倾佩和谢意的重要性。

3
00:00:18.820 --> 00:00:20.820
and having it be specific and genuine.
并使它们听来真诚，具体。

4
00:00:20.820 --> 00:00:22.820
And the way I got interested in this was,
之所以我对此感兴趣

5
00:00:22.820 --> 00:00:25.820
I noticed in myself, when I was growing up,
是因为我从我自己的成长中注意到

6
00:00:25.820 --> 00:00:26.820
and until about a few years ago,
几年前，

7
00:00:26.820 --> 00:00:28.820
that I would want to say thank you to someone,
当我想要对某个人说声谢谢时，

8
00:00:28.820 --> 00:00:29.820
I would want to praise them,
当我想要赞美他们时，

9
00:00:29.820 --> 00:00:31.820
I would want to take in their praise of me
当我想接受他们对我的赞扬，

10
00:00:31.820 --> 00:00:33.820
and I'd just stop it.
但我却没有说出口。

11
00:00:33.820 --> 00:00:36.820
And I asked myself, why?
我问我自己，这是为什么？

12
00:00:36.820 --> 00:00:38.820
I felt shy, I felt embarrassed.
我感到害羞，我感到尴尬。

13
00:00:38.820 --> 00:00:40.820
And then my question became,
接着我产生了一个问题

14
00:00:40.820 --> 00:00:42.820
am I the only one who does this?
难道我是唯一一个这么做的人吗？

15
00:00:42.820 --> 00:00:43.820
So, I decided to investigate.
所以我决定做些探究。

16
00:00:43.820 --> 00:00:46.820
I'm fortunate enough to work in the rehab facility,
我非常幸运的在一家康复中心工作，

17
00:00:46.820 --> 00:00:49.820
so I get to see people who are facing life and death with addiction.
所以我可以看到那些因为上瘾而面临生与死的人。

18
00:00:49.820 --> 00:00:53.820
And sometimes it comes down to something as simple as,
有时候这一切可以非常简单地归结为，

19
00:00:53.820 --> 00:00:58.820
their core wound is their father died without ever saying he's proud of them.
他们最核心的创伤来自于他们父亲到死都未说过“他为他们而自豪”。

20
00:00:58.820 --> 00:01:00.820
But then, they hear from all the family and friends
但他们从所有其它家庭或朋友那里得知

21
00:01:00.820 --> 00:01:03.820
that the father told everybody else that he was proud of him,
他的父亲告诉其他人为他感到自豪，

22
00:01:03.820 --> 00:01:04.820
but he never told the son.
但这个父亲从没告诉过他儿子。

23
00:01:04.820 --> 00:01:07.820
It's because he didn't know that his son needed to hear it.
因为他不知道他的儿子需要听到这一切。

24
00:01:07.820 --> 00:01:11.820
So my question is, why don't we ask for the things that we need?
因此我的问题是，为什么我们不索求我们需要的东西呢？

25
00:01:11.820 --> 00:01:13.820
I know a gentleman, married for 25 years,
我认识一个结婚25年的男士

26
00:01:13.820 --> 00:01:15.820
who's longing to hear his wife say,
渴望听到他妻子说，

27
00:01:15.820 --> 00:01:18.820
"Thank you for being the breadwinner, so I can stay home with the kids,"
“感谢你为这个家在外赚钱，这样我才能在家陪伴着孩子，”

28
00:01:18.820 --> 00:01:19.820
but won't ask.
但他从来不去问。

29
00:01:19.820 --> 00:01:21.820
I know a woman who's good at this.
我认识一个精于此道的女士。

30
00:01:21.820 --> 00:01:23.820
She, once a week, meets with her husband and says,
每周一次，她见到丈夫后会说，

31
00:01:23.820 --> 00:01:27.820
"I'd really like you to thank me for all these things I did in the house and with the kids."
“我真的希望你为我对这个家和孩子们付出的努力而感谢我。”

32
00:01:27.820 --> 00:01:30.820
And he goes, "Oh, this is great, this is great."
他会应和到“哦，真是太棒了，真是太棒了。”

33
00:01:30.820 --> 00:01:32.820
And praise really does have to be genuine,
赞扬别人一定要真诚，

34
00:01:32.820 --> 00:01:34.820
but she takes responsibility for that.
但她对赞美承担了责任。

35
00:01:34.820 --> 00:01:37.820
And a friend of mine, April, who I've had since kindergarten,
一个从我上幼儿园就一直是朋友的叫April的人，

36
00:01:37.820 --> 00:01:40.820
she thanks her children for doing their chores.
她会感谢她的孩子们做了家务。

37
00:01:40.820 --> 00:01:42.820
And she said, "Why wouldn't I thank it, even though they're supposed to do it?"
她说：“为什么我不表示感谢呢，即使他们本来就要做那些事情？”

38
00:01:42.820 --> 00:01:44.820
So, the question is, why was I blocking it?
因次我的问题是，为什么我不说呢？

39
00:01:44.820 --> 00:01:45.820
Why were other people blocking it?
为什么其它人不说呢？

40
00:01:45.820 --> 00:01:48.820
Why can I say, "I'll take my steak medium rare,
为什么我能说：“我要一块中等厚度的牛排，

41
00:01:48.820 --> 00:01:51.820
I need size six shoes," but I won't say,
我需要6号尺寸的鞋子，”

42
00:01:51.820 --> 00:01:53.820
"Would you praise me this way?"
但我却不能说：“你可以赞扬我吗？”

43
00:01:53.820 --> 00:01:57.820
And it's because I'm giving you critical data about me.
因为这会使我把我的重要信息与你分享。

44
00:01:57.820 --> 00:01:59.820
I'm telling you where I'm insecure.
会让我告诉了你我内心的不安。

45
00:01:59.820 --> 00:02:01.820
I'm telling you where I need your help.
会让你认为我需要你的帮助。

46
00:02:01.820 --> 00:02:04.820
And I'm treating you, my inner circle,
虽然你是我最贴心的人，

47
00:02:04.820 --> 00:02:06.820
like you're the enemy.
我却把你当作是敌人。

48
00:02:06.820 --> 00:02:08.820
Because what can you do with that data?
你会用我托付给你的重要信息做些什么呢？

49
00:02:08.820 --> 00:02:10.820
You could neglect me.
你可以忽视我。

50
00:02:10.820 --> 00:02:11.820
You could abuse it.
你可以滥用它。

51
00:02:11.820 --> 00:02:13.820
Or you could actually meet my need.
或者你可以满足我的要求。

52
00:02:13.820 --> 00:02:15.820
And I took my bike into the bike store-- I love this --
我把我的自行车拿到车行－－我喜欢这么做－－

53
00:02:15.820 --> 00:02:18.820
same bike, and they'd do something called "truing" the wheels.
同样的自行车，他们会对车轮做整形。

54
00:02:18.820 --> 00:02:20.820
The guy said, "You know, when you true the wheels,
那里的人说：“当你对车轮做整形时，

55
00:02:20.820 --> 00:02:21.820
it's going to make the bike so much better."
它会使自行车变成更好。”

56
00:02:21.820 --> 00:02:23.820
I get the same bike back,
我把这辆自行车拿回来，

57
00:02:23.820 --> 00:02:26.820
and they've taken all the little warps out of those same wheels
他们把有小小弯曲的铁丝从轮子上拿走

58
00:02:26.820 --> 00:02:29.820
I've had for two and a half years, and my bike is like new.
这辆车我用了2年半，现在还像新的一样。

59
00:02:29.820 --> 00:02:31.820
So, I'm going to challenge all of you.
所以我要问在场的所有人，

60
00:02:31.820 --> 00:02:33.820
I want you to true your wheels:
我希望你们把你们的车轮整形一下：

61
00:02:33.820 --> 00:02:36.820
be honest about the praise that you need to hear.
真诚面对对你们想听到的赞美。

62
00:02:36.820 --> 00:02:38.820
What do you need to hear? Go home to your wife --
你们想听到什么呢？

63
00:02:38.820 --> 00:02:40.820
go ask her, what does she need?
回家问问你们的妻子，她想听到什么？

64
00:02:40.820 --> 00:02:42.820
Go home to your husband -- what does he need?
回家问问你们的丈夫，他想听到什么？

65
00:02:42.820 --> 00:02:45.820
Go home and ask those questions, and then help the people around you.
回家问问这些问题，并帮助身边的人实现它们。

66
00:02:45.820 --> 00:02:46.820
And it's simple.
非常简单。

67
00:02:46.820 --> 00:02:48.820
And why should we care about this?
为什么要关心这个呢？

68
00:02:48.820 --> 00:02:49.820
We talk about world peace.
我们谈论世界和平。

69
00:02:49.820 --> 00:02:52.820
How can we have world peace with different cultures, different languages?
我们怎么用不同的文化，不同的语言来保持世界和平？

70
00:02:52.820 --> 00:02:56.820
I think it starts household by household, under the same roof.
我想要从每个小家庭开始。

71
00:02:56.820 --> 00:02:58.820
So, let's make it right in our own backyard.
所以让我们在家里就把这件事情做好。

72
00:02:58.820 --> 00:03:00.820
And I want to thank all of you in the audience
我想要感谢所有在这里的人们

73
00:03:00.820 --> 00:03:02.820
for being great husbands, great mothers,
因为你们是好丈夫，好母亲，

74
00:03:02.820 --> 00:03:04.820
friends, daughters, sons.
好伙伴，好女儿和好儿子。

75
00:03:04.820 --> 00:03:05.820
And maybe somebody's never said that to you,
或许有些人从没跟你们说过

76
00:03:05.820 --> 00:03:07.820
but you've done a really, really good job.
但你们已经做得非常非常得出色了。

77
00:03:07.820 --> 00:03:10.820
And thank you for being here, just showing up
感谢你们来到这里，

78
00:03:10.820 --> 00:03:13.820
and changing the world with your ideas.
向世界显示着你们的智慧，并用它们改变着世界。

79
00:03:13.820 --> 00:03:15.820
Thank you.
谢谢。

80
00:03:15.820 --> 00:03:22.820
(Applause)
（鼓掌）